      "writtenOn": "2020-08-18T22:29:51Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "I wish we didn\u0027t provide this field. It\u0027d lead to more likely correct usage of GoB API.\nThe only reliable way to query GoB for multiple changes, afaiu, is by adding \"before\" to the query.\n\nI guess one way to solve this is to provide high level wrapper that does the right thing:\n    PagingListChanges(req, query, limit)\nPerhaps I can work on that, since we need it for CQ/Tricium anyway.",
      "revId": "4ead48792bc9bb30e7916672c44dbe10f0f4c100",
      "serverId": "3ce6091f-6c88-37e8-8c75-72f92ae8dfba",
      "unresolved": false
    },
    {
      "key": {
        "uuid": "a5c1ad0d_b4c36ec4",
        "filename": "common/proto/gerrit/gerrit.proto",
        "patchSetId": 4
      },
      "lineNbr": 184,
      "author": {
        "id": 1003190
      },
      "writtenOn": "2020-08-18T22:58:05Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "\"before\"... so what you mean is that in order to page you\u0027d get the timestamp from the earliest change and then to get the next page you\u0027d use before:?\n\nIf this is definitely always the best way to do it, then why don\u0027t we do it that way in this CL? i.e. don\u0027t provide Offset, and (optionally) provide an  earliest timestamp field in the response for convenience?",
      "parentUuid": "d09729b9_b7eff18a",
      "revId": "4ead48792bc9bb30e7916672c44dbe10f0f4c100",
      "serverId": "3ce6091f-6c88-37e8-8c75-72f92ae8dfba",
      "unresolved": false
    },
    {
      "key": {
        "uuid": "68e1919a_0c284131",
        "filename": "common/proto/gerrit/gerrit.proto",
        "patchSetId": 4
      },
      "lineNbr": 184,
      "author": {
        "id": 1114919
      },
      "writtenOn": "2020-08-18T23:41:13Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "Having offset follows actual Gerrit API and using \"before\" correctly is very non-trivial. 2 examples:\n\n1. how to handle the case of:\n    res \u003d list(q, page_size \u003d 25, before \u003c\u003d $tstamp)\n  where each change in result has exactly the same update $tstamp?\n  what should the next query be? Naive implementation would loop forever 😞\n\n2. what if a change is updated while you are paging through?\nNaive impl would totally miss it. And in some cases it\u0027s fine, though then probably using offset is also fine.\nIf you really want to get all changes matching a query, then the proper implementation must page through all of them first and then page again for the most recently updated changes until timestamps start overlapping. This is PITA to implement.\n\nSo, I think it\u0027s much better to provide high level function instead that works around the unfortunate Gerrit API. BTW, another way might be to convince Gerrit to provide optional ordering of changes in the query by their change.number or change.created_time DESC. This would be ~similar to ordering by .updated in practice, but unlike .updated, the ordering is stable and paging is obvious.",
      "parentUuid": "a5c1ad0d_b4c36ec4",
      "revId": "4ead48792bc9bb30e7916672c44dbe10f0f4c100",
      "serverId": "3ce6091f-6c88-37e8-8c75-72f92ae8dfba",
      "unresolved": false
    },
    {
      "key": {
